> There was just a republican state that made it mandatory for teachers to disclose trans individuals to their families. 

There is no right for minors of any type to have the government hide things from their parents, though. Parents expect schools to inform them if their kids get into fights, cut classes, are diagnosed with a disease, are showing signs of suicidality, etc. And the state expects schools to inform the police of students show signs of abuse, etc.

Legally, schools act *in loco parentis* and minors in schools have no expectation or right to privacy with regard to schools hiding things from parents.

So this doesn't violate trans children's rights. They have no such right to violate, same as other children.

> <Organization> are trying to ban things like hormone blockers for teens and other things that make it harder for people to transition.

No one im America has any right to any medical treatment whatsoever, except seriously injured people who make it to an ER -- they can't legally be pushed into the street and abandoned by the hospital. 

And no one has a right to any specific treatment -- if you want viagra and the doctors tell you no, for whatever reason, your rights have not been violated.

So this does not violate trans rights, either.

> There‚Äôs a reason why trans people face such high suicide rates and it‚Äôs from an uncaring and hateful attitude perpetuated against them.

81% of transgender people have one or more personality disorders, with NPD being number one at 57%. This likely explains most trans suicide attempts. Many groups face an uncaring and hateful world and it's rare for more than a token few members to commit suicide. Blacks are a good example. Jews are an even better one -- violently hated by the entirety of <Organization> German society, persecuted, expropriated, regularly beaten and terrorised, and then sent off to slave labor and/or extermination camps, yet their suicide rate barely rose.

External factors do not account for the trans suicide rate. Which, by the way, is not much higher than the non-trans rate in adolescents.

Compartment syndrome is a doozy. Patients typically have some type of trauma to a region of tissue that results in inflammation, leading to swelling and thus cutting off arterial blood supply. The compartment of fascia holding the muscle in place increases in pressure as the tissue occupying it swells more and more. This will then cause veins in the compartment to collapse thus resulting in very poor blood flow in and out, leading to tissue ischemia (death due to lack of O2).

For children, it means that the re-attachment procedure has to take into account the future growth or else, the knee-joint wouldn't be at the right level as an adult. Pretty sure they can approximate the position quite well with growth charts/family height history or something.

In case of an adult, you'd amputate so that the ankle is positioned at knee-height post-operatively since the bone stopped growing already = shorter.

Title: Negotiating Across Cultures

Issues of Culture in Negotiation

Negotiation is the process by which two or more parties attempt to reach an agreement. The goal of negotiation is not necessarily to reach an agreement, but to improve the never-obtainable conditions for an agreement, that is, it reduces uncertainty and risk . Negotiation occurs in a variety of places such as commerce (buying and selling), politics, between individuals, etc.

Negotiation is not just an agreement to complete a task together, but the building of social capital . The investment in relationships with others builds trust. Trust and cooperation are essential to creating "win-win" situations for all parties involved. Therefore it is necessary that negotiations be taken seriously and performed appropriately (Figure 1).

One of the most important aspects to a negotiation is that it includes some element of disagreement. When disagreements are present, the possibility of an adversarial relationship between parties becomes more likely. In negotiations, usually one side prefers a collaborative strategy while another party prefers a competitive strategy. The competitive nature of American society makes the U.S. a very competitive place to do business. To <PersonType>, competition is viewed as being "clean, fair, and square" in which both parties compete openly for the same prize. Furthermore, they feel that it is their duty to win this competition .

A quarter of a century ago, a small crack appeared on the facade of the Evil Empire, a crack that over the following years widened, despite some desperate efforts to plaster it over, and eventually became a giant fissure that brought the whole edifice down.

Ironically, it was one man's jump over a wall that nine years later led to the Wall coming down. On 14 August 1980, the discontent among the workers in shipyards of Gdansk, on the Polish Baltic coast, finally boiled over and a strike action commenced. A young electrician, who had been fired by the management for his political activity, has heard about the strike and climbed over the wall of the shipyard to join his friends and colleagues - and to quickly become their leader. His name was <Person>, and the rest is history - or, as <Person> would say - the end of history.

(here are some

, courtesy of <Organization>, via

)

I was only eight at the time, but I remember that my family had cut short out holiday by the sea when things started heating up in Gdansk. Everyone was fearing the repeat of 1970, when striking shipyard workers were suppressed with much bloodshed by the communist security forces. It didn't quite turn out that way - thank God - and even the martial law a year and a half later proved not to be particularly violent. The long revolution, which culminated in the events of 1989, was relatively bloodless by history's standards. Whatever the injustice of the communist oppression, Poles - and others - never resorted to blowing themselves, and others, up to press their political point. Yet, in the end, the victory was ours.
